    <title>Combined summary - BIP 38 NFC normalisation issue</title>
    <updated>2023-06-09T01:01:39.964754+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2014-July/006263.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The context of the discussion is related to Bitcoin wallet encryption and Unicode characters in passwords. There are concerns about control characters being present in passphrases and their compatibility with JVM-based wallets. Java limitations of 16-bit characters per character are also discussed, which may not support astral planes in certain cases. The conversation revolves around filtering ISO control characters and limiting the spec to the subset of Unicode that all popular platforms can support. The test vector provided for BIP38 implementation was also questioned due to its unrealistic passphrase choice. Black Duck Code Sight is advertised as a tool for enterprise code indexing and searching.Additionally, there are difficulties presented by the Unicode astral plane, and proposals are made to filter ISO control characters to solve the problem. Control characters should be filtered, while whitespace can be problematic but should be allowed. Emoticons such as pile-of-poo are acceptable, but would require substandard approaches such as character blacklists which is not desirable. It is suggested that any implementation wishing to be compatible with JVM-based wallets refuse any passphrase that includes characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (BMP) unless a fix is found.Jeff Garzik recently added an implementation of BIP 38 (password protected private keys) to bitcoinj. He suggests removing test vector 3 as it does not represent any real-world usage of the spec. Given that "pile of poo" is not a character any sane user would put into a passphrase, he questions the value of this test vector. NFC form is intended to collapse things like umlaut control characters onto their prior code point, but here we're feeding the algorithm what is basically garbage so he's not totally surprised that different implementations appear to disagree on the outcome.The email thread discusses an issue with creating a password on iOS devices with astral characters and not being able to enter that password on a JVM wallet. It is suggested that it might be a JVM string library bug that could be reported and fixed. The problem with Unicode astral plane is caused by a plain old (ASCII) control character, \u0000. However, it is assumed that Character.isISOControl() works consistently across platforms.The conversation includes recommendations such as disallowing any character below U+0020 (space) for UI compatibility across many platforms and limiting the spec to the subset of Unicode that all popular platforms can support unless someone can find a fix. It is noted that JVMs may not support certain characters due to their use of 16-bit characters internally, potentially causing issues with BIP 38 implementation. Mike Hearn files a JVM bug to see what the outcome is.The discussion is focused on the limitations of JVMs and Unicode support in Bitcoin. Overall, the conversation focuses on limitations of JVMs and Unicode support in Bitcoin, with suggestions to ban/filter ISO control characters, limit the spec to subsets of Unicode supported by all popular platforms, and disallow certain characters from being used in passphrases.</summary>
